TI Genome-wide association study of production and stability traits in
   barley cultivated under future climate scenarios
SO MOLECULAR BREEDING
LA English
DT Article
DE Carbon dioxide; Climate change; Combined factors; GWAS; Hordeum vulgare;
   Ozone; Temperature
ID HORDEUM-VULGARE L.; SPRING BARLEY; POPULATION-STRUCTURE; GRAIN WEIGHT;
   WHEAT; GROWTH; YIELD; RESPONSES; CEREALS; NUMBER
AB Future barley cultivars will have to produce under the constraints of higher temperature in combination with increased concentrations of atmospheric carbon dioxide and ozone as a consequence of climate change. A diverse set of 167 spring barley genotypes was cultivated under elevated levels of temperature (+5 degrees C) and [CO2] (700 ppm) as single factors and in combination as well as under elevated [O-3] (100-150 ppb) as single factor. The setting in general resembled changes projected by IPCC (AR5) to take place at the end of this century. A genome-wide association study (GWAS) was performed to identify markers for increased primary production under climate change conditions and reveal possible genes of interest. Phenotyped traits included grain yield, number of grains, number of ears per plant, above-ground vegetative biomass, harvest index and stability of the production parameters over the five applied treatments. The GWAS encompassed 7864 SNP markers (Illumina iselect), a compressed mixed linear model with the GAPIT package, and conservative validation of markers. A total of 60 marker-trait associations [-log(10)(P value) 2.97-5.58] were identified, e.g. grain yield under elevated temperature on barley chromosome 2H, static stability of grain yield on 7H, sites for exploitation of elevated [CO2] on 4H and 7H and associations under the two-factor treatment. Marker-trait associations identified from single-factor treatments were not retrieved, when elevated [CO2] and temperature were combined emphasizing the need for multifactor experiments. This GWA study identified markers and chromosome regions to be targeted in breeding for development of climate resilient cultivars.
C1 [Ingvordsen, C. H.; Mikkelsen, T. N.; Jorgensen, R. B.] Tech Univ Denmark, Dept Chem & Biochem Engn, Ctr Ecosyst & Environm Sustainabil, DK-4000 Roskilde, Denmark.
   [Backes, G.] Univ Kassel, Fac Organ Agr Sci, Sect Organ Plant Breeding & Agrobiodivers, D-37213 Witzenhausen, Germany.
   [Lyngkjaer, M. F.] Univ Copenhagen, Dept Plant & Environm Sci, DK-1871 Frederiksberg C, Denmark.
   [Peltonen-Sainio, P.] MTT Agrifood Res Finland, Plant Prod Res, Jokioinen 31600, Finland.
   [Jahoor, A.] Nord Seed AS, DK-8464 Galten, Denmark.
   [Jahoor, A.] Swedish Univ Agr Sci, Dept Plant Breeding, S-23053 Alnarp, Sweden.
RP Ingvordsen, CH (reprint author), Tech Univ Denmark, Dept Chem & Biochem Engn, Ctr Ecosyst & Environm Sustainabil, Frederiksborgvej 399, DK-4000 Roskilde, Denmark.
EM cahi@kt.dtu.dk
RI Lyngkjar, Michael/F-9847-2014
OI Lyngkjar, Michael/0000-0003-2179-7090
FU Nordic Council of Ministers through the network, 'Sustainable primary
   production in a changing climate'; Danish Council for Independent
   Research: Technology and Production Sciences (FTP) via the project
   'Climate Change Effects on Plant Health' [0602-00589B]; COBRA (Core
   Organic II)
FX We thank all involved in the cultivation and harvest procedures and
   Allan Murphy and Esben Hojrup for technical assistance in RERAF during
