TI Development and characterization of high-amylose wheat lines
SO STARCH-STARKE
LA English
DT Article
DE starch; amylose; wheat; breeding
ID BOUND STARCH SYNTHASE; APPARENT HIGH AMYLOSE; RESISTANT STARCH; PASTING
   PROPERTIES; WAXY; ENDOSPERM; PROTEINS; QUALITY; FLOURS; GENES
AB A complete SGP null mutant (Sgp-A1B1D1 null) winter wheat line was crossed with three wheat varieties: Ukrainka', Lona' and Solstice'. Three backcrosses (BCs) were carried out and marker assisted selection used to identify lines carrying all the three mutant alleles for each cross. BC3 and BC(2)xBC(2) F-3,F- F-4 and F-5 lines (2012-2014) were studied in detail for physical (thousand kernel weight), compositional (protein, gluten, amylose) and starch viscosity properties (rapid visco analyser-RVA). Ten triple mutant high-amylose lines (approximate to 40%) were identified among the BC(2)xBC(2) lines, which had high protein content (>14%), low starch content, gluten index, starch viscosity values and thousand kernel weight. Two of these lines had moderately high amylose (approximate to 30%) content, with outstanding gluten quality, but modified starch viscosity properties.
