TI Towards the sugarcane genome sequence and an understanding of polyploidy
SO INTERNATIONAL SUGAR JOURNAL
LA English
DT Article; Proceedings Paper
CT 28th Congress of the International-Society-of-Sugar-Cane-Technologists
CY JUN 24-27, 2013
CL Sao Paulo, BRAZIL
SP Int Soc Sugar Cane Technologists
DE polyploidy; genome sequencing; BAC library; genome assembly
ID CHROMOSOME; ALIGNMENT; GRASSES; PLANTS; WHEAT; TOOL
AB Sugarcane's economic importance is already well established and an appreciation within the research community of its value as a system to aid understanding the complexities of polyploidy is also growing. Over the past decade, sugarcane studies in Australia have identified many markers associated with agronomically important traits. This has been accomplished through the development of genetic maps and large-scale quantitative trait loci (OTL) studies, working towards identifying which genes or regulatory elements underlie these OTL. Over 500 BAC clones were identified by screening the R570 BAC library with gene sequences or DArT markers underlying OTL of interest. The first 72 BAC clones were sequenced to 1982x-41640x coverage using an Illumina HiSeq2000, and a stringent filtering and assembly process using the short read assembler SaSSY produced BAC clones assemblies with a total size of -7.9 Mbp, -0.08% of the R570 genome. These BACs were each assembled into between 1 and 13 contigs which will likely be improved when combined with shotgun sequence information from an R570 mate-pair library (to be sequenced shortly). These BAC sequences, along with our remaining 400 BACs for which sequencing is currently underway, will provide a multi-locus partial genome sequence of the sugarcane clone R570. Illumina sequencing is demonstrated to provide assembly results which are as good as or better than with the 454 platform while also providing a greater throughput. With many great advances in sugarcane genomics on the horizon, sugarcane presents a highly relevant system in which to investigate polyploid genome evolution and the process of diploidisation. New and robust approaches that build on existing knowledge are yet required to fully de-convolute the complexity of sugarcane's ploidy and its impact on genetic and physiological variability.
C1 [Berkman, P. J.; Casu, R. E.; Stiller, J.; Rae, A. L.; Aitken, K. S.] CSIRO Plant Ind, St Lucia, Qld 4067, Australia.
RP Berkman, PJ (reprint author), CSIRO Plant Ind, 306 Carmody Rd, St Lucia, Qld 4067, Australia.
EM Paul.Berkman@csiro.au
RI Berkman, Paul/G-8678-2011; Rae, Anne/I-3813-2012
OI Berkman, Paul/0000-0002-6523-4356; 
