TI Genetic assessment of common bean (Phaseolus vulgaris L.) accessions by
   peroxidase gene-based markers
SO JOURNAL OF THE SCIENCE OF FOOD AND AGRICULTURE
LA English
DT Article
DE common bean; peroxidase gene-based markers; genetic diversity;
   population structure
ID CLASS-III PEROXIDASES; LENGTH POLYMORPHISMS; ARABIDOPSIS-THALIANA;
   SEQUENCE-ANALYSIS; DROUGHT STRESS; LINKAGE MAP; DIVERSITY; RAPD; FAMILY;
   WHEAT
AB BACKGROUNDPeroxidase, a plant-specific oxidoreductase, is a heme-containing glycoprotein encoded by a large multigenic family in plants. Plant peroxidases (POXs, EC 1.11.1.7) play important roles in many self-defense interactions in plants. Here, 67 common bean (Phaseolus vulgaris L.) genotypes were studied using a POX gene-based marker method. Comparison of POX genes could resolve evolutionary relationships in common bean.
   RESULTSEighty fragments were obtained with 20 primer pairs that amplified one (POX8c) to eight (ATP29) bands, with a mean of four bands per primer pair. The average (polymorphic information content) PIC value for the POX products was 0.40. The maximum variation (93%) was found between Turkey (#33) and India (#52) and between Antalya (#33) and India (#53). The minimum variation (0%) was found among four pairs: Bozdag (#2) and Karadeniz (#38), Kirklareli (#11) and Turkey (#15, 16, 43), Bandirma (#13) and Turkey (#15, 16, 43), and Kirklareli (#10) and Bandirma (#22). UPGMA was used to discriminate the common bean genotypes into five clusters, while STRUCTURE software was used to investigate the genetic population structure.
   CONCLUSIONThe results showed that POX gene family markers can be used to study genotypic diversity and provide new information for breeding programs and common bean improvement practices. (c) 2013 Society of Chemical Industry
