TI Development and Identification of a 4HL.5DL Wheat/Barley Centric Fusion
   Using GISH, FISH and SSR Markers
SO CEREAL RESEARCH COMMUNICATIONS
LA English
DT Article
DE Triticum aestivum; Hordeum vulgare; 4H(4D) substitution line; 'Chinese
   Spring' ph1b mutant; 4HL.5DL centric fusion
ID INDUCED HOMOEOLOGOUS RECOMBINATION; CHROMOSOME ADDITION LINES; BARLEY
   CHROMOSOME; MOLECULAR CHARACTERIZATION; WHEAT; RESISTANCE; TOLERANCE;
   LOCUS; GENE; TRANSLOCATIONS
AB The 4H(4D) wheat/barley substitution line was crossed with the 'Chinese Spring' ph1b mutant genotype in order to induce wheat-barley homoeologous recombinations. F-3 and F-4 seeds of the 4H(4D) x 'Chinese Spring' ph1b mutant cross were analysed using genomic in situ hybridization, and a Robertsonian translocation was detected in monosomic form. Disomic centric fusions were selected among the self-fertilized progenies. The presence of the long arm of 4H was confirmed with SSR markers. The long arm of the 5D wheat chromosome in the Robertsonian translocation was identified using fluorescent in situ hybridization with the help of three DNA probes: pSc119.2, Afa family and pTa71. The wheat/barley centric fusion was identified as a 4HL.5DL translocation. This line exhibited supernumerary spikelet character, but the number of seeds/plant did not increase. The 4HL.5DL centric fusion line is suitable genetic material to study the expression of genes located on 4HL in a wheat genetic background.
