TI In Vitro Culture of Petunia hybrida Microspores and
   Agrobacterium-mediated Transient Expression of beta-glucuronidase (GUS)
   Reporter Gene
SO INTERNATIONAL JOURNAL OF AGRICULTURE AND BIOLOGY
LA English
DT Article
DE Petunia hybrida; Microspores; In vitro culture; Agrobacterium-mediated;
   Transformation
ID GERM-LINE TRANSFORMATION; POLLEN GERMINATION; TRITICUM-AESTIVUM;
   INVITRO; TOBACCO; MATURATION; GROWTH; TUMEFACIENS; MARKER; GRAINS
AB In this study, we developed two optimal media for in vitro culture of microspores and germination of mature pollen in Petunia hybrida. The optimal medium for in vitro culture of microspores was 15% sucrose + MS salts + White's vitamins, pH = 6.0 with the maturation and germination rate of 41.77% and 5.38%, respectively, and the optimal medium for germination of mature pollen was 15% sucrose + 20 mg/L H2BO3 + 10 mg/L CaCl2 +10% PEG(4000), pH = 5.8. The germination rates of matured microspores in vivo and in vitro were 69.82% and 19.87%, respectively. In addition, a system of Agrobacterium-mediated transient expression of beta-glucuronidase (GUS) reporter gene in late unicellular and bicellular pollen was also established. We co-cultivated late unicellular and bicellular pollen of P hybrida with Agrobacterium tumefaciens strain EHA105 harboring the plasmid pBI121 with GUS reporter gene under the control of CaMv35S promoter, respectively. The optimal conditions consisted of an OD600 of 0.3 and infection time of 10 min, and we obtained 70.82% of GUS transient expression frequency for late unicellular pollen and 79.33% for bicellular pollen. (C) 2013 Friends Science Publishers
