TI Barley and Wheat Share the Same Gene Controlling the Short Basic
   Vegetative Period
SO JOURNAL OF INTEGRATIVE AGRICULTURE
LA English
DT Article
DE basic vegetative period; candidate genes; Hordeum; Triticum
ID QUANTITATIVE TRAIT LOCI; PSEUDO-RESPONSE-REGULATOR; HORDEUM-VULGARE L.;
   COMPARATIVE GENOMICS; POWDERY MILDEW; FLOWERING TIME; CHROMOSOME 5AL;
   SPRING BARLEY; HEADING TIME; SE GENE
AB Basic vegetative period (BVP) is an important trait for determining flowering time and adaptation to variable environments. A short BVP barley mutant is about 30 d shorter than its wild type. Genetic analysis using 557 F-2 individuals revealed that the short BVP is governed by a single recessive gene (BVP-1) and was further validated in 2.090 F-3 individuals. The BVP-1 gene was first mapped to barley chromosome 1H using SSR markers. Comparative genomic analysis demonstrated that the chromosome region of BYP-1 is syntenic to rice chromosome 5 and Brachypodium chromosome 2. Barley ESTs/genes were identified after comparison with candidate genes in rice and Brachypodium; seven new gene-specific markers were developed and mapped in the mapping populations. The BVP-1 gene co-segregated with the Mot1 and Ftsh4 genes and was flanked by the gene-specific markers AK252360 (0.2 cM) and CA608558 (0.5 cM). Further analysis demonstrated that barley and wheat share the same short BVP gene controlling early flowering.
