TI Discovery of High-Confidence Single Nucleotide Polymorphisms from
   Large-Scale De Novo Analysis of Leaf Transcripts of Aegilops tauschii, A
   Wild Wheat Progenitor
SO DNA RESEARCH
LA English
DT Article
DE Aegilops tauschii; expression sequence tag; next generation sequencing;
   single nucleotide polymorphism; wheat
ID TRITICUM-AESTIVUM L.; D-GENOME DIVERSITY; FULL-LENGTH CDNAS; HEXAPLOID
   WHEAT; BREAD WHEAT; NATURAL VARIATION; FLOWERING TIME; F-1 HYBRID;
   SEQUENCE; BARLEY
AB Construction of high-resolution genetic maps is important for genetic and genomic research, as well as for molecular breeding. Single nucleotide polymorphisms (SNPs) are the,predominant class of genetic variation and can be used as molecular markers. Aegilops tauschii, the D-genome donor of common wheat, is considered a valuable genetic resource for wheat improvement. Our previous study implied that Ae. tauschii accessions can be genealogically divided into two major lineages. In this study, the transcriptome of two Ae. tauschii accessions from each lineage, lineage 1 (L1) and 2 (L2), was sequenced, yielding 9435 SNPs and 739 insertion/deletion polymorphisms (indels) after de novo assembly of the reads. Based on 36 contig sequences, 31 SNPs and six indels were validated on 20 diverse Ae. tauschii accessions. Because almost all of the SNP markers were polymorphic between L1 and L2, and the D-genome donor of common wheat is presumed to belong to L2, these markers are available for D-genome typing in crosses between common wheat varieties and L1-derived synthetic wheat. Due to the conserved synteny between wheat and barley chromosomes, the high-density expressed sequence tag barley map and the hypothetical gene order in barley can be applied to develop markers on target chromosomal regions in wheat.
C1 [Julio Cesar Masaru, Iehisa; Shigeo, Takumi] Kobe Univ, Grad Sch Agr Sci, Lab Plant Genet, Nada Ku, Kobe, Hyogo 6578501, Japan.
   [Akifumi, Shimizu] Univ Shiga Prefecture, Dept Biol Resources Management, Sch Environm Sci, Hikone, Shiga 5228533, Japan.
   [Kazuhiro, Sato] Okayama Univ, Inst Plant Sci & Resources, Kurashiki, Okayama 7100046, Japan.
   [Shuhei, Nasuda] Kyoto Univ, Grad Sch Agr, Lab Plant Genet, Kyoto 6068502, Japan.
RP Shigeo, T (reprint author), Kobe Univ, Grad Sch Agr Sci, Lab Plant Genet, Nada Ku, Kobe, Hyogo 6578501, Japan.
EM takumi@kobe-u.ac.jp
